                    </labels>
                <created>Thu, 19 Feb 2026 19:22:35 +0000</created>
                <updated>Sat, 21 Feb 2026 06:31:55 +0000</updated>
                                                                                <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>5</watches>
                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="488487" author="adilger" created="Sat, 21 Feb 2026 06:31:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;It makes sense to allow large folio size for IOs up to stripe size, preferring to have larger folios to reduce the overhead of managing the pages. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, I thought there was also a minimum folio size that was enforced, so that block size &amp;gt; page size is possible for ext4 and xfs?  Not to say that we want to enforce this for all files, but it would be useful to be able to enforce this for compressed files. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="488361" author="stancheff" created="Fri, 20 Feb 2026 05:09:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;mmap faulting is still in PAGE_SIZE chunks, however the vmf-&amp;gt;page could be a PAGE_SIZE chunk within a larger folio so the vmf-&amp;gt;pgoff is needed to locate the fault itself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However it looks like current (default) fault logic is to operate on the entire folio containing the page, faulting in any pages ...&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="488357" author="stancheff" created="Fri, 20 Feb 2026 04:35:08 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;folio order is determined in ll_write_begin() so len is limited to the stripe maximum.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With mapping_set_folio_order_range() and mapping_set_large_folios() enabled for the mapping __filemap_get_folio() may return a folio up to the size requested in fgf_flags which is typically:&lt;br/&gt;
    FGP_WRITEBEGIN | fgf_set_order(len)&lt;br/&gt;
where len is additionally limited to cli-&amp;gt;cl_max_pages_per_rpc&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The returned folio may be any size up to the maximum requested, the minimum is order-0 and, of course, -ENOMEM if cache is exhausted.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As memory gets more fragmented over time the only certainty is there will be some order 0 folios regardless of the size requested.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
